Canada
[1] Ontario: multiple provinces, poultry
Date: Fri 1 Apr 2022
Source: Farms.com [edited]
https://www.farms.com/ag-industry-news/fifth-case-of-bird-flu-found-in-ontario-210.aspx


Ontario has at least 5 cases of bird flu.

The Canadian Food Inspection Agency (CFIA) on [31 Mar 2022] confirmed a case of H5N1 in a poultry flock in the Township of Chippewas of Nawash Unceded First Nation in Bruce County.

The premises is under quarantine and CFIA is recommending increased biosecurity measures.

The CFIA confirmed another case of H5N1 the day before [30 Mar 2022] in a poultry flock in Woolwich, Ont.

These cases follow 2 additional cases of H5N1. One discovered in a poultry flock in Zorra, Ont. on [28 Mar 2022] and another in a poultry flock in Guelph on [27 Mar 2022].

These are also in addition to the CFIA confirming a case of H5N1 in a red-tailed hawk in Waterloo Region on [21 Mar 2022].

In response to the positive confirmations, the Feather Board Command Centre, created to be the central figure in Ontario's risk management strategy of the province's chicken, egg, turkey and hatchery sectors, issues a biosecurity advisory to all Ontario producers.

The 5 Ontario cases of avian influenza bring the total number of confirmed cases in Canada to 13.

Other provinces have their own issues with bird flu as well. Between Nova Scotia and Newfoundland and Labrador, another 7 cases. The instances of bird flu in those 2 provinces led multiple countries to impose bans on Canadian poultry.

[Byline: Diego Flammini]

