******
[8] Minnesota (Stearns and Morrison Counties): commercial and backyard flocks
Date: Fri 1 Apr 2022
Source: TwinCities.com [edited]
https://www.twincities.com/2022/04/01/two-more-minnesota-poultry-flocks-infected-with-avian-influenza-state-says/


Two additional poultry flocks are confirmed infected with avian influenza in Minnesota, according to the state Board of Animal Health.

A backyard flock of 115 unspecified birds in Stearns County, the 2nd diagnosis in the county, and a commercial flock of 52 000 turkeys in Morrison County were confirmed infected with H5N1 highly pathogenic avian influenza on Thursday [31 Mar 2022].

The new infections were reported Friday [1 Apr 2022]. The new confirmations bring the total infected flocks in the state to 7 and the number of birds affected by the outbreak to 378 998.

The 1st cases of H5N1 in Minnesota were confirmed [25 Mar 2022], according to the Board of Animal Health.

The earlier confirmations were in commercial turkey flocks in Kandiyohi, Lac qui Parle, Meeker and Stearns Counties and a backyard flock in Mower County.

Farms raising turkeys and chickens for consumption have been on high alert and taking steps to increase biosecurity since avian influenza was recently discovered in a handful of states.

Avian influenza is an airborne respiratory virus spreading easily among chickens through nasal and eye secretions, as well as manure. The virus can spread from flock to flock by wild birds, through contact with infected poultry.

According to state officials, the current outbreak in Minnesota poses little risk to the public and there is no food safety concern for consumers.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED Rapporteur Mahmoud Orabi

[If possible, keep your flocks inside to protect them from co-mingling with wild birds. And remember you can transport this virus on boots, hands or even your coveralls. Be sure you are in clean gear before entering your birdhouses, and also blow your nose before entering a poultry house and again when leaving the poultry house.

Biosecurity of your flock is hugely important in protecting them. It is not just a word, but an action to protect your flocks.

Most wild bird species, as well as poultry and other domestic birds, are neither tolerant nor resistant to HPAI viruses, and thus they become ill and do not move much, which implies they are poor spreaders and instead they may act as sentinels of viral circulation. Consequently, please be on alert for the least sign of a bird not feeling well or not eating. Early detection can help limit losses. - Mod.TG]
